column1: 181047;instagram;2019-01-15 18:57:25;FALSE;"this was my truck. this truck saved my life
column2: where my exhusband tried to end it. i lied to the police and said i was driving
column3: when infact it was denn(who was drunk
column4: smoked marijuana&later i found out did meth that day
column5: before we took adderall together).i didnt care that he had just spent 30 minutes belittling me shortly before this
column6: i didnt care that he had got into a tussle with me before this
column7: i didnt care that he had just torn me a new one for mentioning his lack of license
column10: and the odds of an accident(this was at the party store not even 3 minutes before he yet again almost took my life). this was super bowl sunday. we were going to see my friend lexy. the cashier said to me ""you can stay here&we will find you a safe ride to your friend"". as denn threatened to leave me there if i ""didnt get my ass in the truck"". once in the truck he accused me of flirting with the cashier&started yelling at me(he was always cheating
column11: so his thought process/paranoia was that i was also or to accuse me so he wouldnt be caught). he took off out of the parking lot of the party store on the corner of cork&kilgore
column12: 2 minutes later he lost control&ran my side of the truck into a street sign
column13: mailboxes&a fire hydrant. had this truck not been designed so safely
column14: i would be dead or had been severely injured.

column1: there was no time to hesitate. denn was freaking out that he was going to go to jail. we had alcohol in the back cab&marijuana on us. i immediately shoved food in my mouth to cover the scent of alcohol the best i could
column2: claimed i was the driver. i crafted a very believable story&had him repeat it to me until ours were barely different(not the first time). i then threw the alcohol in the bed of the truck under some things. called my insurance company&the police showed up. i'm pretty sure the officer knew i was lying for denn. he took us home
column3: no charges or a search. he wouldnt have life w/out me.

column1: i think one of the hardest things is not accepting the abuse that occured

column1: 181081;instagram;2019-01-15 19:31:17;FALSE;"how they used dr. mlk to decieve the world! #facts
among its other accusations are that:
dr king took part in ""drunken sex orgies"" and coerced young women to participate
he had love affairs with at least four women
the list of alleged indiscretions would likely have been deeply problematic for the civil rights leader if it had been made public in 1968.
from 1870 to 1955 schools like dunbar high school in washington dc¬†equaled or scored higher on standardized test scores than white schools.
from 1890 to 1950 every census report showed blacks at a higher participation rate in employment than whites.
in 1950 72% of black men had been married.
in 1950 81% of black women had been married.
black poverty was on the decline.
less black families were on government assistance.
black income was on the rise for black population in comparison to whites.
in 1965 76.4% of black children were born to married women.

the french connection was a scheme through which heroin was smuggled from turkey to france and then to the united states through canada. the operation reached its peak in the late 60s and early 70s
column2: and was responsible for providing the vast majority of the heroin used in the u.s

column2: a bay area drug ring sold tons of cocaine to the crips and bloods street gangs of los angeles and funneled millions in drug profits to a latin american guerilla army run by the u.s. central intelligence agency¬†source@oigjustoc.gov

among its other accusations are that:
dr king took part in ""drunken sex orgies"" and coerced young women to participate
he had love affairs with at least four women
the list of alleged indiscretions would likely have been deeply problematic for the civil rights leader if it had been made public in 1968.
from 1870 to 1955 schools like dunbar high school in washington dc¬†equaled or scored higher on standardized test scores than white schools.
from 1890 to 1950 every census report showed blacks at a higher participation rate in employment than whites.
in 1950 72% of black men had been married.
in 1950 81% of black women had been married.
black poverty was on the decline.
less black families were on government assistance.
black income was on the rise for black population in comparison to whites.
in 1965 76.4% of black children were born to married women.

among its other accusations are that:
dr king took part in ""drunken sex orgies"" and coerced young women to participate
he had love affairs with at least four women
the list of alleged indiscretions would likely have been deeply problematic for the civil rights leader if it had been made public in 1968.
from 1870 to 1955 schools like dunbar high school in washington dc¬†equaled or scored higher on standardized test scores than white schools.
from 1890 to 1950 every census report showed blacks at a higher participation rate in employment than whites.
in 1950 72% of black men had been married.
in 1950 81% of black women had been married.
black poverty was on the decline.
less black families were on government assistance.
black income was on the rise for black population in comparison to whites.
in 1965 76.4% of black children were born to married women.

column1: 181182;instagram;2019-01-15 21:31:51;FALSE;"you can always tell when i'm having a rough patch because i break out the grey's anatomy quotes.
it's been a bit of a struggle to start 2019
column2: not going to lie. even though i've already had a fun trip and am planning to do more activism and volunteering
column3: the annual ""why did this happen to me"" train of thought is slowly creeping around the mountain and choking me with its steam. i didn't leave my bed for 3 days... just laid around and thought of ""what could've been"" had i decided to break up with him over the phone instead of in-person.
i had to make the choice to get up. to leave my bed and work through my anxiety as best i could...to breathe and to show up for myself.

column1: am i the best version of lee today? absolutely not. but i showed up anyway! when i read this quote
column2: i always remind myself that this can apply to me too. i can be kinder and more compassionate with me when i'm struggling with survival. today i decided that even a bad day is better than no day at all... and that's just enough to keep me looking forward to tomorrow
column3: where i can work on being a more kind and compassionate person to myself and others.

column1: for anyone else struggling today or any other day
column2: i feel you and i love you

column1: 7. you were never really here by lynne ramsay

both ""first reformed"" & ""you were never really here"" are about haunted men deconstruct. if the former felt a little messy at times (in a good way)
column2: this film is made with masterful precision & sharp psychological insights.

column1: 181387;instagram;2019-01-16 01:05:54;FALSE;"this is from an online message board but i found it to be so accurate. it's so scary
when i knew i was being mistreated by my ex h i insisted that we go to therapy and i voiced my concerns about the way he spoke to me and had treated me when our dog got sick and died.
he and the therapist determined that i was the problem.  it was my emotional overreaction to the dog dying that was the problem
column2: not his abusive language and i felt unheard
column3: unsupported and lost. he did exactly what the piece described and came across as perfect and i was the problem. anyone who was there described me as incredibly calm and collected in my emotions
column4: while sad i never was unreasonable and he was lying but in a way that made it impossible for me to defend.

column1: when i finally got the right help ten years later my therapist was shocked by this
column2: it was clear to him that my ex h was incredibly abusive and he would have advised me to leave and knowing myself i would have listened

column1: he agreed that knowing me he knows i would have left and apologized for the failure of the therapy i received and that it truly resulted in more pain and trauma for no reason. i could have left the relationship at that point and never turned to alcohol but i didn't because i was ashamed of myself for my emotions and drank more to escape.

addiction is rooted in pain and trauma and often times we never know the truth about what is happening behind closed doors.  if you are being misunderstood in therapy get a new therapist and don't be ashamed to leave a marriage after 6 months. it's far better than becoming addicted to alcohol. my ex h eventually got mad at me for drinking sparkling water
column2: eating bread and butter and would give me the silent treatment when i ate these foods because he was disappointed in me. when i got promoted he told me i didn't need to celebrate with cake
column3: too many calories. it's so wonderful to be free from that life and it all got much worse after that therapist. he was empowered and i was weakened üò•

column1: it‚Äôs no shocker if you‚Äôve been following along that this last year kicked my butt. climbing and trekking around in the himalayan mountains up to everest base camp solo the past few weeks gave me hours upon hoursssss to sit and be with my own thoughts. i learned three great lessons while trekking and the first one is this:
i‚Äôve always leaned on great teachers like maya angelou who says
‚Äúit's one of the greatest gifts you can give yourself
‚Äúi think the hardest thing in life is to forgive. hate is self destructive. if you hate somebody
column2: you're not hurting the person you hate
column3: you're hurting yourself. it's a healing

column1: but the statement that really grabbed me was the first one by nelson mandela....about letting go of bitterness to find freedom.
i believe after my assault the emotions of anger and bitterness were masked by anxiety
column5: ptsd and depression. i honestly didn‚Äôt realize that bitterness over the trauma and those who turned their backs to me was an issue until i had all those hours alone to ponder. and then i noticed that the emotions of bitterness and resentment were holding me back and i wasn‚Äôt going to have that anymore. i‚Äôm coming up on a year of therapy and doing the hard work. i‚Äôve confronted and spoken my truth despite the fear. i‚Äôve done the damn things needed to heal except let go of the bitterness.

column1: this point on the trek. this exact point...was when i let it all go. it was that simple. let it go. with a few deep breaths i let go of anger
column2: bitterness and embraced total forgiveness. it was the greatest gift i could give to myself. since this moment
column3: i have felt so much peace and calm deep in my soul. forgiveness doesn‚Äôt mean i ever want to invite the abuser or the betrayers to my home or for a coffee...it simply means ‚Äúi am done with you.‚Äù

matthew 15 has one of the most troubling passages in the gospels in my opinion.  verses 21-28 have an exchange between jesus and an unnamed canaanite woman.  she comes to jesus asking for jesus to heal her daughter.  but jesus‚Äô first response is to flat out ignore her.  as she persists
column2: jesus then responds by saying that he was only sent to the ‚Äúlost sheep of israel‚Äù and then tells her what sure sounds like he is saying that to do what she was asking would be like taking food and throwing it to the dogs.  now
column3: there are lots of ways that this passage has been interpreted in the past to try to make it more palatable and several of those interpretations have some strong validity.  however
column5: an honest reckoning with this passage makes one have to ask if jesus was having a really bad day that day or what was going on with him.  after all
column6: this was the same guy who hung out with the outcasts
column7: who talked with the samaritan woman that no one else would
column8: who rescued the woman who was going to be killed for adultery
column9: and so forth.  even if there is a palatable interpretation of this
column10: honest reckoning opens the door to want to ask jesus
column11: ‚Äúwhat the heck?‚Äù honest reckoning to me is like crossing a snow and ice covered bridge.  one needs to do it in order to move forward but it is often more difficult than the path leading to the bridge.  we‚Äôve all seen those signs ‚Äúbridge ices before road‚Äù right?  but the bridge still needs to be crossed.  it can be difficult and it takes more time but it is what is needed.  #ayearwithjesus #reckoning #nativeamericans #racism #ptsem #bridge /1";;en;#ayearwithjesus

;2019 spesial 30 tahun tragedi junko furuta . 16 - everything need know movement gerakan ( atau gerakan dengan beragam nama alternatif lokal dan internasional , adalah gerakan melawan pelecehan seksual dankekerasan seksual . menyebar secara viral pada bulan oktober 2017 sebagai tagar di media sosial dalam upaya untuk menunjukkan prevalensi yang luas dari pelecehan dan pelecehan seksual , terutama di tempat kerja . itu terjadi segera setelah tuduhan pelecehan seksual terhadap harvey weinstein . tarana burke , seorang aktivis sosial amerika dan pengorganisir komunitas , mulai menggunakan frasa `` '' sejak tahun 2006 , dan frasa ini kemudian dipopulerkan oleh aktris amerika alyssa milano , di twitter pada tahun 2017. milano mendorong para korban pelecehan seksual untuk tweet tentang hal itu dan `` memberi orang rasa besarnya masalah '' . ini disambut dengan sukses yang termasuk tetapi tidak terbatas pada posting profil tinggi dari beberapa selebriti amerika , termasuk gwyneth paltrow , ashley judd , jennifer lawrence , dan uma thurman . tarana burke , seorang aktivis sosial dan pengorganisir komunitas , mulai menggunakan frasa `` '' pada tahun 2006 , di jejaring sosial myspace sebagai bagian dari kampanye untuk mempromosikan `` pemberdayaan melalui empati '' di antara wanita kulit berwarna yang telah mengalami pelecehan seksual , khususnya dalam komunitas yang kurang mampu . burke , yang membuat film dokumenter berjudul , mengatakan ia terinspirasi untuk menggunakan frasa tersebut setelah tidak mampu meggapi seorang gadis berusia 13 tahun yang mengaku kepadanya bahwa ia telah dilecehkan secara seksual . burke kemudian berharap dia hanya memberi tahu gadis itu , `` aku juga '' . alyssa milano mendorong penggunaan hashtag setelah tuduhan terhadap harvey weinstein muncul pada tahun 2017 . column1: 181699;instagram;2019-01-16 08:45:30;FALSE;"when i was coming to terms with my past
column2: i took myself back through it as i tried to piece together events

column1: i felt that because i couldn't remember things they may not have happened and that the holes that i had would mean that people may not believe me.
i learnt three things which i have carried with me for many years.

1. i don't need to remember fully the deepest details of my abuse to begin to heal. my brain is deeply powerful and i have remembered all i need to in order to break free. kids who have lived through trauma often have few memories.
2. i don't need to share with others the dates
column2: times etc of my abuse to make them believe me.

column1: some people have believed me and other's havent. those who question my story do so for their own reasons. i cannot control them and now choose to shut my ears to their questions
they did not see and they cannot know.
3. i am stronger than i ever knew. my past enhanced that resilience and strength but it was always within me. those who question my story also question the changes in me. they saw me as once weak
column3: quiet and  timid. that person is my past.

column1: i wave at her in my mirror as i look back to see how far i have come. the past is hazy and a little foggy but the road ahead is brightly lit.
whether they are clear or muted
wave at the past as you glance back in that rear view mirror and know that you have the whole road ahead on which to travel.

181767;instagram;2019-01-16 10:49:59;FALSE;characteristics of low porosity hair (e.g 4c hair) : ‚úî cuticles tightly coiled.
‚úî moisture has hard time getting in.
‚úî lack of moisture leaves hair dry
it is crucial for low prosity to open the cuticles up and this can be achieved with damp heat.
note: do not use too much protein like coconut oil or black castor oil. instead use lighter oils and shea butter. honey which is a natural humectant is also fantastic for low porosity hair.
because of the tightly packed cuticles
column2: low porosity hair is prone to product build up - products tend to sit on the hair and not penetrate. protein rich oils e.g coconut oil used too frequently will make the hair harder as they fill gaps in the hair cuticle.

column1: the go to oils for low porosity hair are: üå∫baobab oil üå∫ argan oil üå∫grapeseed oil üå∫sunflower oil
the go to butters are: üå∫ shea butter

column1: 181819;instagram;2019-01-16 12:20:18;FALSE;i don't remember much of my childhood the majority of the things i do remember seem to be fictional. i'm the last of 9 siblings 4 siblings (the golden children) could do or say no wrong unfortunately the remaining siblings and myself had a hard childhood. i was sexually abused between the ages of 11 and 14 as i remember. i believe this is why i blocked out most of my childhood. since my mental breakdown in 2002 when i was at the age of 31 up to 2013 when i had my breakthrough as i call it. i dealt with and try to face all of my demons and problems that was and is no easy task. it is also something i will have to maintain doing for the rest of my life but at least i have a healthier relationship and understanding off my life. i did not come to the full conclusion that i was a transgender man until 2015. now although i portrayed all the signature marks like not feeling feminine but more like a boy. dressing

column1: harassment is a form of discrimination. it includes any unwanted physical or verbal behavior that offends or humiliates you. it can come in many shapes and forms.

column3: people who are being harassed are not even aware of it. and if one does not even know that they are being harassed
column4: how can one speak against it?

column2: i have made a list of the most common forms of harassment: ‚Ä¢	if someone makes unwelcome remarks or jokes about your race
column7: etc. ‚Ä¢	if someone threatens or intimidates you because of your race
column12: etc. ‚Ä¢	if someone makes unwelcome physical contact with you
column15: or pinching.  it is very important to understand that harassment is not limited to sexual harassment
column16: especially in the workplace. some common examples of workplace harassment are shown in the picture above. on the other hand
column17: sexual harassment is the form of harassment that is seen everywhere. in many cases
column19: women are reluctant to come forward with allegations of sexual harassment in a country where many still blame the woman themselves for such wrongs. this is where we have to change our thinking
column20: and stand up against all kinds of harassers. since harassment can be subject to both genders

column1: i watched season 2 episode 5 of #netflix original series ‚Äúglow‚Äù last night- you know that show about the first female wrestling team in the glorious 80s- and it struck a chord. no! an entire nerve!
i need not get into recap and  #metoo or #timesup referencing here. we all know - in the wake of current affairs.
but here is a story that came back up last night like regurgitated half digested food:

when i was working in la in 2000 i interviewed with a very prominent talent agency. i was called in for a meeting with a junior agent for a role in the (in) famous mailroom which is the place almost every aspiring talent agent in hollywood starts in order to work their way up to executive level in tinseltown.
now we all know that thanks to hbo‚Äôs #entourage which has since set the standard for non- insiders of hollywood life to muse on the goings-on.
i walked in and was ushered to the agent‚Äôs office by the pretty young receptionist.

column2: the first thing that struck me was how attractive he was. tall
column4: handsome and devilishly aware of his charisma. the door closed and i was alone in the room with him.

column1: i was 23. i was blond. i was tanned. and i was wearing black pants and a blazer with high heels. nothing enticing there.

next thing i know is: he is pulling down the blinds in the entire 360 fish bowl office and with a nonchalant chuckle and the words: ‚Äúwhere do you see yourself in 5 years?‚Äù - he starts unbuttoning his shirt.
my heart stopped for a second. then started racing. everyone in that place

i did a ‚Äúruth‚Äù then: like the protagonist in ‚Äúglow‚Äù i ran. i mumbled: thank you but no thank you or something resembling that and dashed for the door. i remember sitting in my car minutes later; heart pounding in my chest
column4: hands shaking as i pulled out of the parking lot.

column1: and i didn‚Äôt know what to do.
needless to say i didn‚Äôt get that job nor did i ever work for an agency.
i never met the agent again - even though he became one of the major players in hollywood.

column1: i dont exactly remember my age but i might be 5-6 years when we shifted our home. i was really excited for having new neighbours and friends to play with.
everything went well until i met this guy who was probably 6-8 years elder to me.
i thought him as my brother
column2: he used to give me choclates everyday until one day when i was playing with my friends he called me to his room for some help and grabbed me in his blanket and kissed me on my lips. i was numb . i didnt knew how to react . i just pushed him and ran away. after this i decided not to go near him but one fine day he grabbed me again and did the same thing . i was helpless . i didnt had the courage to go and speak to my parents and tell them all the things that happend to me . but thankfully this all ended as we shifted again to a new place .

column1: ‚Ä¢ i was really small when this all happend to me and i didnt had the courage to speak to my parents but this memory still haunts me. i didnt tell this to anyone yet but i wanted to share my story to the world so that i can request all the people who are seeing this post to protect you wives
column2: daugters and sisters . and to all the parents out there
column3: pleasee talk to your children and tell them whats right and wrong
column4: make them brave so that they can fight against it. make them so brave that if something like this happens( i pray it doesnt) to them they can have courage to come and speak to you.
